It should be noticed that Sprat's book received the sanction oi the Royal Society, and that copies oi it were sent by them to foreign princes and other eminent persons on the continent. Hence Liebig's sneer at Sprat (Aligemeine Zeitung, March 7, 18⁶4), unless he is prepared to extend it generally to the members oi the Royal Society at that time, is entirely out of place.

But there is much more evidence to the same effect. The cele· brated mathematician‚ Dr. Wallis, in the very interesting Account of some Passages oi his own Lise, published in Appendirn Num. xi, to Heame's Presace to Peter Langtoft’s Chronicle¹⁹, says: ‘About the year 1645, while 1 lived in London, * * * * * I had the opportunity of being acquainted with divers worthy Persons, inquisitiva into Natural Philosophy, and other parts of Humane Learning3 and particularly oi what hath been called the New Philosophy or Ex- perimental Philosophy! He then proceeds to give the names of his associates and their places of maeting. ‘Our business was to Discourse and consider oi Philosophical Enquiries, and such as related there· untol * * * * * ‘Some oi which were then but New discoveries, and others not so generally known and imbraced, as now they are, with other things appertaining to what hath been called The New Philosophy ; which from the times oi Galileo at Florence, and Sir Francis Bacon (Lord Verulam) in England, harh been much culti· vated in Italy, France‚ Germany, and other parts abroad‚ as well as with us in England!
